Vector Autoregression (VAR) models are widely used for forecasting because they capture the dynamic interdependencies among multiple time series variables, often outperforming simpler structural models that impose restrictive assumptions. While VARs lack direct theoretical interpretations (ruling out C and F), they do not require all variables to be stationary (E is incorrect), and their coefficients are not inherently positive (A is false). VARs are indeed used for forecasting, and their performance can exceed that of standalone models in many cases.
